d de Vigny, Alphonse de Lamartine, and Victor Hugo. Ribner assesses the ways in which legislation imagery became an instrument of political propaganda, and he clearly illuminates the cult of the law as it became personalized under Napoleon, monarchist under the Restoration, and defensive under Louis-Phillipe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4ahistory of art. 4alaw related to other disciplines. 4alaw. 4amotives. 4apainting. 4apolitics. 4athe arts. 4atopics. 7aART / European.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520308893?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520308893423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520308893/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles